text.Taxonomy and naming:
The species was first formally described by Robert Chinnock in 1979 and the description was published in the Journal of the Adelaide Botanic Gardens. The type specimen was collected by Chinnock about 17 kilometres (10 mi) south east of Yarrabubba homestead. The specific epithet is from Latin, meaning 'cobwebby', alluding to the long hairs in the corolla tube.Two subspecies are recognised by the Australian Plant Census:

Eremophila arachnoides  Chinnock  subsp. arachnoides, commonly known as spider web eremophila, which has distinctly hairy leaves;
Eremophila arachnoides subsp. tenera  Chinnock , commonly known as slender-leaved eremophila, has glabrous leaves.The epithet tenera is from the Latin meaning 'slender', referring to the long, slender leaves.
